Recommended Readings on Ebonics -- tScholarly References and News Titles0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aControversy erupted in 1996 when the Oakland Unified School District’s ‘Ebonics Resolution’ proposed an approach to teaching Standard English that recognized the variety of English spoken by African American students. With new demands for accountability driven by the No Child Left Behind policy and its emphasis on high-stakes testing in Standard English, this debate will no doubt rise again. This book seeks to better inform this next episode. In Part 1, leading scholars place the debate within its historical and contemporary context, provide clear explanations of what Ebonics is and is not, and offer practical approaches schools can and should follow to address the linguistic needs of African American students. Part 2 provides original documents that accompanied the debate, including the original resolutions, legislation, organization position papers, and commentary/analyses from leading linguists. This book is written for all those whose work impacts the lives of Ebonics speakers in our public schools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducation. 0aBlack English. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxAfrican American students. 0aLanguage and educationxSocial aspectsxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxBlack EnglishxUSA. 0aLanguage and educationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aAfrican American students.  aEbonics Resolution.  aNo Child Left Behind.  aOakland Unified School District.  aStandard English.  ahigh-stakes testing.  aurban education.1 aAdger, Carolyn Temple, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaugh